  "output": "Confirmed. All findings check out against the actual source. Here's the analysis.\n\n## Performance audit — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python job-scanning pipeline (async `httpx` fetchers → SQLite dedup store → filter → notify), running every 12h via GitHub Actions cron. Not a React codebase, so I skipped re-render analysis and focused on the patterns that actually apply here.\n\n### What's already good (no fix needed)\n- `fetchers.py:1126` `fetch_all()` fetches all ~80 sources **concurrently** via a shared `httpx.AsyncClient` + `asyncio.Semaphore` — no sequential N+1 HTTP pattern.\n- Pagination loops (`fetch_apple`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, etc.) use `set()` for dedup checks — no O(n²) list scans.\n- `Store` is always used via `with ... as store:` — no leaked connections/cursors.\n- Each cron run is a fresh process, so no cross-run in-memory state accumulation.\n\n### 1. N+1 SQLite round trips in `Store.diff()` — highest impact\n`store.py:55-74`\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\nWith ~80 sources and paginated boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Google up to 400 listings each), a single run can produce thousands of `Job` rows — each doing a separate `SELECT` plus a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. That's thousands of round trips on every scheduled run.\n\n**Fix** — one bulk `SELECT` (chunked to stay under SQLite's ~999-variable bind limit) to build an in-memory lookup, then `executemany` for the writes:\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i+900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?'*len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        touched.append(job)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(key) DO UPDATE SET ...\", [...])  # single upsert per job, batched\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n(SQLite's `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE` collapses insert/update into one `executemany` call.)\n\n### 2. Regex recompiled per job in the filter hot path\n`filters.py:11-12, 21-26`\n```python\ndef _compile(words): return [re.compile(rf\"\\b{re.escape(w)}\\b\", re.IGNORECASE) for w in words if w]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n`filter_jobs()` (line 44) calls `match()` once per fetched job — thousands of times per run — and each call recompiles the same 10 exclude / 4 include patterns from `sources.yaml`. That's tens of thousands of redundant `re.compile()` calls for patterns that never change within a run.\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs()`, pass compiled patterns down:\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include_re=None, exclude_re=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude_re and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude_re):\n        return False\n    if include_re and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include_re):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include_re=include_re, exclude_re=exclude_re, ...)]\n```\n\n### 3. No conditional-GET caching on repeat fetches (lower confidence)\n`fetchers.py` — `_simple()`-based sources (60+ boards on greenhouse/lever/smartrecruiters/recruitee/workable) do a full fresh GET every 12h with no ETag/`If-Modified-Since`. Most listings won't have changed between runs, so this is pure re-download cost. Worth adding conditional-GET headers keyed by URL if the ATS platforms support them (Greenhouse's `boards-api` does return `Last-Modified`) — but not confirmed across all providers, so treat as a nice-to-have rather than urgent.\n\n### 4. Unbounded `jobs.db` / `jobs` table growth\n`store.py` has no pruning of delisted postings, and the workflow commits `jobs.db` back to the repo every run. Over months this makes both the diff workload (item 1) and the git history grow indefinitely. Consider a `last_seen < now - N days` cleanup pass, or archiving stale rows out of the hot table.\n\n**Priority order**: fix #1 and #2 first — they're pure algorithmic waste on every single scheduled run and scale with listing count, which is only growing as more sources get added. #3 and #4 are worth doing but lower urgency.\n",
